[
  {
    "id": "finnish-defence-forces",
    "name": "Finnish Defence Forces (Suomen Puolustusvoimat)",
    "nation": "Finland",
    "service": "National Armed Forces",
    "type": "National Army",
    "theater": "Eastern Front (Finnish sector)",
    "active": {
      "from": "1939-11-30",
      "to": "1944-09-19"
    },
    "flag": "/public/images/flags/finland.svg",
    "commanders": [
      {
        "name": "Marshal Carl Gustaf Emil Mannerheim (Supreme Commander)",
        "period": "Nov 1939–Aug 1944"
      }
    ],
    "peak_strength": "500,000 (Continuation War, 1941)",
    "summary": "The Finnish Defence Forces conducted two wars against the Soviet Union: the Winter War (1939–1940) and the Continuation War (1941–1944). Under Mannerheim they resisted the Soviet Union to a negotiated peace in both cases, preserving Finnish independence. Finland fought alongside Germany but maintained a distinct war aim — recovery of territory lost in 1940 — and refused German requests to advance on Leningrad.",
    "context": "The Winter War (30 November 1939–13 March 1940) saw Finland resist the Soviet invasion for 105 days — far longer than expected — at a ratio of approximately 1:7 in manpower and 1:30 in aircraft. The Mannerheim Line and Finnish defensive tactics inflicted enormous losses on the Red Army before weight of numbers prevailed. Finland ceded 11% of its territory and 30% of its economic capacity. In the Continuation War (June 1941–September 1944), Finland advanced to the 1940 border and beyond but stopped short of Leningrad at Mannerheim's insistence, despite intense German pressure. The separate peace with the Soviet Union (September 1944) and subsequent Lapland War against Germany preserved Finnish independence — the only Nazi-allied country to emerge with sovereignty intact.",
    "overview_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The Finnish Defence Forces occupy a distinct position among the Axis Allies documented in this archive: unlike Italy, Romania, or Hungary, Finland was never a member of the Axis alliance in any formal or ideological sense. It fought alongside Germany for pragmatic reasons of national survival, having been invaded by the Soviet Union in 1939, and its war aims remained narrowly focused on recovering territory lost in that earlier conflict rather than on any shared Axis project."
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "images": [
          {
            "src": "/public/images/flags/finland.svg",
            "caption": "Flag of Finland",
            "description": "Finnish forces fought the Soviet Union in two separate wars between 1939 and 1944 while maintaining political distance from the wider Axis alliance."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Under Marshal Mannerheim, one of the most respected military leaders of the war on any side, Finland fought the Winter War and the Continuation War as essentially separate conflicts bound by the same underlying cause, and emerged from both with its independence and core territory intact — a record matched by no other state that fought alongside Germany against the Soviet Union. Within this archive, the Finnish Defence Forces should be read as a case apart from the other Axis Allies entries, illustrating that 'fighting alongside Germany' did not always mean sharing Germany's wider war aims."
      }
    ],
    "context_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "The Winter War",
        "text": "The Winter War, from 30 November 1939 to 13 March 1940, saw Finland resist the Soviet invasion for 105 days — far longer than almost anyone expected — despite facing the Red Army at a manpower ratio of roughly 1:7 and an aircraft ratio of roughly 1:30. The Mannerheim Line and skilled Finnish defensive tactics inflicted enormous losses on Soviet forces before sheer weight of numbers eventually prevailed, and Finland was forced to cede 11 percent of its territory and 30 percent of its economic capacity in the resulting peace."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "The Continuation War",
        "text": "In the Continuation War, from June 1941 to September 1944, Finland advanced to recover its 1940 border and somewhat beyond, but stopped well short of participating in the siege of Leningrad despite intense and repeated German pressure to do so — a decision taken personally by Mannerheim that distinguished Finland's war aims clearly from Germany's own."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "A Separate Peace",
        "text": "Finland's separate peace with the Soviet Union in September 1944, followed by the brief Lapland War against German forces still on Finnish soil, preserved Finnish independence and territorial integrity — making it the only state allied with Germany against the Soviet Union to emerge from the war with its sovereignty fully intact."
      }
    ],
    "sources": [
      {
        "type": "primary",
        "ref": "Suomen Sota 1941–1945. Finnish General Staff, 1958–1994. 9 vols."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Screen, J.E.O. Mannerheim: The Finnish Years. Hurst, 2000."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Trotter, William. A Frozen Hell: The Russo-Finnish Winter War of 1939–40. Algonquin, 1991."
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
      {
        "id": "carl-mannerheim",
        "title": "Carl Mannerheim",
        "type": "Personnel"
      },
      {
        "id": "leningrad",
        "title": "Siege of Leningrad",
        "type": "Campaign"
      },
      {
        "id": "barbarossa",
        "title": "Operation Barbarossa",
        "type": "Campaign"
      },
      {
        "id": "vol-002",
        "title": "Bergström — Hanko, Finland (1941)",
        "type": "Letter"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "italian-10th-army",
    "name": "10ª Armata Italiana (Italian 10th Army)",
    "nation": "Italy",
    "service": "Regio Esercito",
    "type": "Army",
    "theater": "North Africa",
    "active": {
      "from": "1940-06",
      "to": "1941-02"
    },
    "flag": "/public/images/flags/italy.svg",
    "commanders": [
      {
        "name": "Generale d'Armata Mario Berti",
        "period": "Jun–Dec 1940"
      },
      {
        "name": "Generale d'Armata Italo Gariboldi",
        "period": "Dec 1940–Feb 1941"
      }
    ],
    "peak_strength": "236,000 (Jan 1941)",
    "fate": "Destroyed at Beda Fomm, February 1941.",
    "summary": "The Italian 10th Army invaded Egypt from Libya in September 1940, advancing 100 kilometres before halting. Wavell's Operation Compass (December 1940) counterattacked with a force seven times smaller and in two months destroyed the 10th Army completely — capturing 130,000 prisoners, 400 tanks, and 1,290 guns at a cost of 1,900 British casualties.",
    "context": "Operation Compass (9 December 1940 – 7 February 1941) under General Richard O'Connor remains one of the most spectacular victories in British military history. The attack was intended as a five-day raid; it became a campaign of annihilation. The 10th Army was outfought at every level — its artillery was outranged, its tanks obsolete, its tactical doctrines rigid. The capture of 130,000 prisoners with barely 30,000 British and Commonwealth troops forced Hitler to send Rommel's Afrikakorps to prevent Italy's complete ejection from North Africa. The 10th Army never recovered as an effective formation.",
    "overview_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The Italian 10th Army represented Fascist Italy's principal field force in North Africa at the outset of the war in the Mediterranean theater, and its catastrophic destruction in early 1941 is one of the clearest illustrations in this archive of the gap between the scale of Italy's colonial ambitions and the actual combat readiness of its armed forces."
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "images": [
          {
            "src": "/public/images/flags/italy.svg",
            "caption": "Flag of Fascist Italy",
            "description": "Germany's principal Axis partner and the originator of the North African campaign the 10th Army's destruction effectively ended."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Its invasion of Egypt in September 1940 was intended to demonstrate Italian military power independent of German support, fulfilling Mussolini's own ambitions for a 'parallel war' alongside, rather than dependent on, Germany. Its destruction by a vastly smaller British force just months later forced exactly the German intervention — the dispatch of Rommel's Afrikakorps — that Mussolini had hoped to avoid, fundamentally altering the character of the entire North African campaign for the rest of the war."
      }
    ],
    "context_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "Operation Compass",
        "text": "Operation Compass, fought from 9 December 1940 to 7 February 1941 under the British General Richard O'Connor, remains one of the most spectacular victories in British military history. The attack was originally intended as a five-day raid to disrupt Italian positions; instead, finding Italian resistance collapsing rapidly, O'Connor pressed the advantage and turned it into a campaign of near-total annihilation."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "A One-Sided Defeat",
        "text": "The 10th Army was outfought at virtually every level of combat — its artillery was outranged by British guns, its tanks were obsolete against even the limited British armour available, and its tactical doctrine proved far too rigid for the fluid desert warfare that followed. The capture of some 130,000 Italian prisoners by a British and Commonwealth force of barely 30,000 troops stands as one of the most lopsided victories of the entire war."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "Consequences",
        "text": "The scale of the defeat forced Hitler to dispatch Rommel's Afrikakorps to North Africa to prevent Italy's complete ejection from the continent — a decision with consequences extending far beyond the immediate battle, since it drew German forces into a theater that would eventually consume substantial resources better needed elsewhere. The 10th Army itself never recovered as an effective fighting formation for the remainder of the war."
      }
    ],
    "sources": [
      {
        "ref": "Bierman, John and Smith, Colin. War Without Hate. Penguin, 2002."
      },
      {
        "ref": "O'Connor, Richard. Papers. Churchill College, Cambridge."
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
      {
