        "id": "erwin-rommel",
        "title": "Erwin Rommel",
        "type": "Personnel"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "romanian-3rd-army",
    "name": "Armata a 3-a Română (Romanian 3rd Army)",
    "nation": "Romania",
    "service": "Armata Română",
    "type": "Army",
    "theater": "Eastern Front",
    "active": {
      "from": "1942-08",
      "to": "1942-11"
    },
    "flag": "/public/images/flags/romania.svg",
    "commanders": [
      {
        "name": "General Petre Dumitrescu",
        "period": "Aug–Nov 1942"
      }
    ],
    "peak_strength": "152,000 (November 1942)",
    "fate": "Destroyed by Soviet Operation Uranus, 19–23 November 1942.",
    "summary": "The Romanian 3rd Army held the northern flank of the German 6th Army at Stalingrad — the weakest point of the entire front. Soviet Operation Uranus struck through the Romanian positions on 19 November 1942, breaking through in hours and encircling the 6th Army. The Romanian forces collapsed in the face of Soviet armoured columns they could not stop.",
    "context": "The Romanian 3rd Army's position north of Stalingrad and the 4th Romanian Army to the south were the recognised weak points of the Axis front — known to German intelligence, reported by Romanian commanders, and apparently known to Soviet planners. Romanian anti-tank weapons could not penetrate Soviet T-34 armour. When Uranus struck on 19 November 1942, the front broke immediately. Within four days the two Soviet pincers had closed behind the 6th Army. The destruction of the Romanian armies effectively ended Romania's military effectiveness as an Axis partner; by 1944 Romania had switched sides and was fighting against Germany.",
    "overview_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The Romanian 3rd Army was one of two Romanian field armies committed to the Stalingrad sector of the Eastern Front in 1942, contributing the single largest non-German contingent to the Axis order of battle in that campaign. Romania's participation in the war against the Soviet Union stemmed primarily from its own territorial dispute with the USSR over Bessarabia and northern Bukovina, annexed by the Soviets in 1940, giving Romanian forces a war aim distinct from, though aligned with, Germany's own."
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "images": [
          {
            "src": "/public/images/flags/romania.svg",
            "caption": "Flag of Romania",
            "description": "Romania's 3rd and 4th Armies held the flanks of the German 6th Army at Stalingrad and bore the brunt of the Soviet encirclement that destroyed it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Its destruction in November 1942, alongside the parallel collapse of the Romanian 4th Army to the south, was a direct and foreseeable consequence of being assigned to hold an exposed sector of the front with equipment unable to counter Soviet armour — a failure of German operational planning as much as of Romanian fighting capacity. Within this archive, the 3rd Army's record connects directly to the 6th Army and Battle of Stalingrad entries, since the encirclement of the German force at Stalingrad was made possible specifically by the Romanian front's collapse."
      }
    ],
    "context_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "The Weak Point of the Front",
        "text": "The Romanian 3rd Army's position to the north of Stalingrad, together with the Romanian 4th Army to the south, were the recognised weak points of the entire Axis front in the sector — a vulnerability known to German intelligence, reported repeatedly by Romanian commanders themselves, and apparently well understood by Soviet planners preparing their counteroffensive."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "Operation Uranus",
        "text": "Romanian anti-tank weapons could not penetrate the armour of the Soviet T-34, the tank that formed the spearhead of the Soviet assault. When Operation Uranus struck on 19 November 1942, the Romanian front broke almost immediately, and within four days the two converging Soviet pincers had closed behind the German 6th Army, sealing its fate."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "Consequences for the Alliance",
        "text": "The destruction of the Romanian armies effectively ended Romania's military usefulness as an Axis partner for the remainder of the campaign season, and the political fallout proved lasting: by August 1944, with Soviet forces approaching Romanian territory directly, Romania switched sides entirely and joined the war against Germany."
      }
    ],
    "sources": [
      {
        "ref": "Axworthy, Mark, Scafes, Cornel and Craciunoiu, Cristian. Third Axis, Fourth Ally: Romanian Armed Forces in the European War. Arms and Armour, 1995."
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
      {
        "id": "stalingrad",
        "title": "Battle of Stalingrad",
        "type": "Campaign"
      },
      {
        "id": "6th-army",
        "title": "6th Army",
        "type": "Formation"
      },
      {
        "id": "blue",
        "title": "Operation Blue",
        "type": "Campaign"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "hungarian-2nd-army",
    "name": "Magyar 2. Hadsereg (Hungarian 2nd Army)",
    "nation": "Hungary",
    "service": "Magyar Királyi Honvédség",
    "type": "Army",
    "theater": "Eastern Front",
    "active": {
      "from": "1942-04",
      "to": "1943-02"
    },
    "flag": "/public/images/flags/hungary.svg",
    "commanders": [
      {
        "name": "Vezérezredes Gusztáv Jány",
        "period": "Apr 1942–Feb 1943"
      }
    ],
    "peak_strength": "207,000",
    "fate": "Destroyed in Soviet Ostrogozhsk–Rossosh offensive, January 1943.",
    "summary": "The Hungarian 2nd Army held the Don River front to the south of the German lines at Stalingrad. The Soviet Ostrogozhsk–Rossosh offensive (January 1943) destroyed the army in four days, killing or capturing approximately 148,000 men — the greatest military catastrophe in Hungarian history.",
    "context": "Like the Romanian formations, the Hungarian 2nd Army was stationed on a vulnerable sector of the Eastern Front with inadequate anti-tank weapons, no reserves, and a 200-kilometre front to hold. The January 1943 offensive — launched simultaneously with the final destruction of the 6th Army at Stalingrad — broke through in hours. The army disintegrated; survivors streamed westward in winter temperatures of minus 40°C with no coherent rear supply. Hungary's political relationship with Germany never recovered. Admiral Horthy began exploring ways to exit the war; Germany pre-empted him by occupying Hungary in March 1944.",
    "overview_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The Hungarian 2nd Army was Hungary's principal contribution to the Eastern Front campaign of 1942, assigned to hold a long and exposed stretch of the Don River line to the south of the German 6th Army's positions at Stalingrad. Hungary's alliance with Germany, like Romania's, was driven substantially by territorial disputes — in Hungary's case, the desire to retain or recover land lost to neighbouring states after the First World War."
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "images": [
          {
            "src": "/public/images/flags/hungary.svg",
            "caption": "Flag of Hungary",
            "description": "Hungary's 2nd Army suffered the greatest single military catastrophe in the country's history during the Soviet offensive of January 1943."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Its destruction in January 1943, in an offensive that struck almost simultaneously with the final collapse of the German 6th Army at Stalingrad, is remembered in Hungarian national memory as the single greatest military catastrophe in the country's history — a scale of loss that permanently damaged Hungary's relationship with Germany and set the stage for the country's later, ultimately unsuccessful attempt to exit the war independently."
      }
    ],
    "context_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "An Exposed Front",
        "text": "Like the Romanian formations to the north, the Hungarian 2nd Army was stationed on a dangerously exposed sector of the Eastern Front, equipped with anti-tank weapons inadequate against Soviet armour, possessing no significant reserves, and responsible for holding some 200 kilometres of front with insufficient troop density to do so securely."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "The Ostrogozhsk–Rossosh Offensive",
        "text": "The Soviet offensive of January 1943 — launched in close coordination with the final destruction of the German 6th Army at Stalingrad — broke through the Hungarian positions within hours of beginning. The army disintegrated almost completely; survivors streamed westward through winter temperatures as low as minus 40 degrees Celsius, with no coherent rear-area supply system to support their retreat."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "Political Fallout",
        "text": "Hungary's political relationship with Germany never recovered from the scale of this loss. Admiral Miklós Horthy, Hungary's regent, began quietly exploring ways to exit the war and seek a separate peace with the Allies; Germany pre-empted any such move by occupying Hungary outright in March 1944, ending what remained of the country's independent decision-making for the rest of the conflict."
      }
    ],
    "sources": [
      {
        "ref": "Ungváry, Krisztián. Battle for Budapest: 100 Days in World War II. I.B. Tauris, 2003."
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
      {
        "id": "stalingrad",
        "title": "Battle of Stalingrad",
        "type": "Campaign"
      },
      {
        "id": "romanian-3rd-army",
        "title": "Romanian 3rd Army",
        "type": "Formation"
      },
      {
        "id": "blue",
        "title": "Operation Blue",
        "type": "Campaign"
      }
    ]
  }
]

germany\\armies.json:
[
  {
    "id": "6th-army",
    "name": "6. Armee (6th Army)",
    "nation": "Germany",
    "service": "Heer",
    "type": "Army",
    "theater": "Eastern Front",
    "active": {
      "from": "1939",
      "to": "1943-02-02"
    },
    "commanders": [
      {
        "name": "Generalfeldmarschall Walter von Reichenau",
        "period": "1939–Jan 1942"
      },
      {
        "name": "Generaloberst Friedrich Paulus",
        "period": "Jan 1942–Feb 1943"
      }
    ],
    "peak_strength": "430,000 (Aug 1942)",
    "fate": "Destroyed at Stalingrad. Surrendered 2 February 1943.",
    "summary": "The 6th Army under Paulus captured Kharkov, drove to the Volga, and fought the Battle of Stalingrad — the most destructive battle in history. Encircled by Operation Uranus in November 1942, it surrendered on 2 February 1943. Of 300,000 encircled, approximately 91,000 survived to surrender; fewer than 6,000 ever returned to Germany.",
    "context": "The 6th Army was the spearhead of Army Group B's drive to Stalingrad in the summer of 1942. By September it was fighting house-to-house in the city. The Soviet counteroffensive Operation Uranus (19 November 1942) broke through the flanking Romanian armies and encircled the entire 6th Army. Hitler refused permission to break out when escape was still possible. Göring's assurance that the Luftwaffe could supply 300 tons per day proved catastrophically false — an average of 90 tons per day was actually delivered. The relief attempt (Operation Winter Storm, December 1942) was halted 50 kilometres from the pocket. The army fought on through January 1943 in temperatures of minus 30°C, without adequate food, ammunition, or medical care. Paulus surrendered on 2 February 1943 — the same day Hitler promoted him to Generalfeldmarschall, fully expecting him to commit suicide rather than be taken prisoner.",
    "overview_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "6th Army was a field army of the Heer — the echelon directly below an army group, typically commanding several corps and numbering several hundred thousand men. It existed from before the war and served in the Polish and French campaigns, but it is overwhelmingly remembered for a single episode: its destruction at Stalingrad, the costliest single battle of the Second World War and arguably of human history."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Under Friedrich Paulus, the army formed the spearhead of the 1942 summer offensive (Operation Blue) toward the Volga and the city that bore Stalin's name — a target chosen as much for its symbolic value as for any decisive strategic necessity. Its encirclement and annihilation over the winter of 1942–43 marked the turning point of the war in the East and the first unambiguous, irreversible German strategic defeat."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Within this archive, 6th Army's record connects directly to the Battle of Stalingrad campaign entry, to Army Group B (its parent command), and to the broader catastrophe that also consumed the Romanian armies guarding its flanks — a chain of related records that together document one of the war's most thoroughly studied campaigns."
      }
    ],
    "context_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "The Drive to the Volga",
        "text": "The 6th Army was the spearhead of Army Group B's drive to Stalingrad in the summer of 1942. By September it was fighting house-to-house in the city, in combat so close and so attritional that German soldiers coined the term Rattenkrieg — rat war — to describe it."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "Encirclement",
        "text": "The Soviet counteroffensive Operation Uranus (19 November 1942) broke through the weaker Romanian armies guarding the 6th Army's flanks and encircled the entire force within days. Hitler refused permission to break out while escape was still possible, insisting the army hold its position and be resupplied by air."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "The Airlift and Winter Storm",
        "text": "Göring's assurance that the Luftwaffe could supply 300 tons per day to the trapped army proved catastrophically false — an average of only around 90 tons per day was actually delivered, far short of the minimum needed to sustain the force. The relief attempt, Operation Winter Storm in December 1942, was halted some 50 kilometres from the pocket and never reached the encircled troops."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "Surrender",
        "text": "The army fought on through January 1943 in temperatures as low as minus 30 degrees Celsius, without adequate food, ammunition, or medical care. Paulus surrendered on 2 February 1943 — the same day Hitler promoted him to Generalfeldmarschall, fully expecting him to commit suicide rather than be taken prisoner, since no German field marshal had ever previously surrendered. Paulus declined to do so."
      }
    ],
    "sources": [
      {
        "type": "primary",
        "ref": "Bundesarchiv-Militärarchiv, Freiburg. RH 20-6: 6th Army operational files, 1941–1943."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Beevor, Antony. Stalingrad. Viking, 1998."
      },
      {
        "ref": "Craig, William. Enemy at the Gates: The Battle for Stalingrad. Dutton, 1973."
      }
    ],
    "related_records": [
      {
        "id": "stalingrad",
        "title": "Battle of Stalingrad",
        "type": "Campaign"
      },
      {
        "id": "blue",
        "title": "Operation Blue",
        "type": "Campaign"
      },
      {
        "id": "kharkov",
        "title": "Third Battle of Kharkov",
        "type": "Campaign"
      },
      {
        "id": "de-001",
        "title": "Schreiber — Stalingrad (1942)",
        "type": "Letter"
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "id": "4th-panzer-army",
    "name": "4. Panzerarmee (4th Panzer Army)",
    "nation": "Germany",
    "service": "Heer",
    "type": "Panzer Army",
    "theater": "Eastern Front",
    "active": {
      "from": "1941-11",
      "to": "1945"
    },
    "commanders": [
      {
        "name": "Generaloberst Erich Hoepner",
        "period": "Nov 1941–Jan 1942"
      },
      {
        "name": "Generaloberst Hermann Hoth",
        "period": "May 1942–Nov 1943"
      },
      {
        "name": "Generaloberst Erhard Raus",
        "period": "Nov 1943–Aug 1944"
      }
    ],
    "peak_strength": "c. 350,000 (July 1943, Kursk)",
    "summary": "The 4th Panzer Army was Germany's premier armoured formation on the Eastern Front. Under Hoth it led the summer offensive into the Don bend and drove to within 50 kilometres of the encircled 6th Army at Stalingrad. It formed the southern arm of the Kursk offensive (Operation Citadel) in July 1943 — the largest tank battle in history.",
    "context": "The 4th Panzer Army's history tracks the arc of German fortunes in the East. In the summer of 1942 it drove across the steppe toward Stalingrad as part of Operation Blue. In December 1942, Hoth led the relief attempt (Operation Winter Storm), reaching the Aksai River before being halted by Malinovsky's 2nd Guards Army — forever 50 kilometres from the trapped 6th Army. At Kursk in July 1943, the 4th Panzer Army formed the more powerful southern pincer, with SS Panzer Corps and 48th Panzer Corps achieving the deepest penetration of Soviet defences before Operation Citadel was cancelled. The tank battle at Prokhorovka on 12 July 1943 — often called the largest armoured engagement in history — was fought by units of the 4th Panzer Army. After Kursk the army fought a continuous defensive battle as Soviet offensives pushed it steadily westward.",
    "overview_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "4th Panzer Army was one of the principal armoured field armies of the Wehrmacht on the Eastern Front, sitting at the same echelon as 6th Army but distinguished by its composition: rather than predominantly infantry, it commanded panzer and motorized corps, giving it the speed and striking power for the deep, mobile operations that characterised German offensive doctrine."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Formed from Panzer Group 4 in 1942, it served under Army Group South and its successor commands for most of its existence, fighting in three of the most heavily documented engagements of the Eastern Front: the drive to Stalingrad and the failed relief of the trapped 6th Army, the southern pincer at Kursk, and the immense tank battle at Prokhorovka. Its history is therefore closely intertwined with — but operationally distinct from — that of 6th Army, which it tried and failed to rescue in December 1942."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Within this archive, 4th Panzer Army is most usefully read alongside the 6th Army, I. SS-Panzerkorps, and Battle of Stalingrad records, since all four describe overlapping moments of the same southern-front campaign from different organizational perspectives."
      }
    ],
    "context_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "Operation Blue and the Drive South",
        "text": "The 4th Panzer Army's history tracks the arc of German fortunes in the East. In the summer of 1942 it drove across the open steppe toward Stalingrad as part of Operation Blue, the offensive intended to seize the Caucasus oilfields while also securing the Volga at Stalingrad to protect the operation's northern flank."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "title": "Winter Storm",
